# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adam-stegerwald
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] State elections were held in the Free State of Prussia on 20 February 1921 to elect 406 of the 428 members of the Landtag of Prussia.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] The governing coalition of the Social Democratic Party, Centre Party, and German Democratic Party suffered major losses, losing one-third of its total vote share from 1919, but retained a narrow majority.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] The right-liberal German People's Party (DVP) and right-wing nationalist German National People's Party (DNVP) made the largest gains, with the DNVP becoming the second largest party by vote share.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] The Communist Party of Germany contested its first Prussian election, winning 31 seats.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] No election was held on the constituency of Oppeln due to the Upper Silesia plebiscite, which was held one month after the state elections.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] The delegation of 22 deputies which had been elected in Oppeln in 1919 continued in office until a 1922 by-election.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] The discrepancy between these results meant that the Centre Party held more seats in the Landtag than the DNVP after the 1921 election, despite winning fewer votes.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] No election took place in constituency #9 (Oppeln); for this purpose, members of this constituency elected in the 1919 election retained their seats.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1921-prussian-state-election] Note: shaded boxes indicate the party that won the most votes in the constituency.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The **1932 Prussian coup d'état** or ***Preußenschlag*** (German pronunciation: [ˈpʁɔʏsənˌʃlaːk]; lit.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 'Prussian hit') took place on 20 July 1932, when Reich President Paul von Hindenburg, at the request of Franz von Papen, then Reich Chancellor of Germany, replaced the legal government of the Free State of Prussia with von Papen as Reich Commissioner.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] A second decree the same day transferred executive power in Prussia to the Reich Minister of the Armed Forces Kurt von Schleicher and restricted fundamental rights.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] One was that the 1932 Prussian state election had left a divided parliament with no viable possibilities for a coalition.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] This led to a caretaker government under the coalition that had held power before the election, with no clear path to replacing it with a new governing coalition.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The second and major rationale was that in parts of Prussia there were violent street demonstrations and clashes taking place that Papen said the caretaker government could not control.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The immediate result was elimination of the last resistance in Prussia to Papen's attempt to establish a "New State", essentially a precursor to a restored monarchy.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] However, the coup also weakened the federalist Constitution of the Weimar Republic and ultimately facilitated the centralization of the Reich under Adolf Hitler after he was appointed chancellor in January 1933.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Since the late 1920s the relationship between the Reich and Prussia had been the subject of discussion by the League for the Renewal of the Reich (*Bund zur Erneuerung des Reiches*), a group to which von Papen belonged.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The program included having the Reich president, the Reich government and the Reichstag replace the Prussian government and parliament, and empowering the chancellor to appoint provincial commissioners.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] It was assumed that Prussia, contrary to the interest of the entire nation, was as a state pursuing hegemony within the existing national structure.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] A comprehensive segmentation and disempowerment was proposed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] A constitutional committee was appointed to draw up workable proposals for constitutional and administrative reform and for prudent financial management.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] On 21 June 1930 the assessments were presented.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The reform effort faced objections primarily from Bavaria and Prussia.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Bavaria, the second largest state, objected because it feared that the proposal would immediately unify the northern German states while the south would gain only a reprieve from becoming part of a unified, non-federal Reich.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Papen's long-term goal was to restore the Hohenzollern monarchy.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The ‘New State’ was to stand above particularist interests and provide the necessary security, order, and tranquility for economic development.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The Free State of Prussia had been governed since 1920 by a stable coalition of the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), the Catholic Centre Party and the German Democratic Party (DDP).
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In the 1932 Prussian state election of 24 April, the Nazi Party (NSDAP) won 162 seats and the Communist Party of Germany (KPD) 57, a total of 219 out of 423, or 52%.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] All other parties together won only 204 seats, or 48%.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The NSDAP and KPD would not work together, and none of the other parties could form a government with a parliamentary majority without the support of one of the anti-democratic parties, something that none of them was willing to accept.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] That meant that after the formal resignation of the previous state government – the third cabinet of Otto Braun – it remained in office on a caretaker basis in accordance with Article 59 of the state constitution.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] With parliamentary rules having recently been changed to require an absolute majority for the election of a minister president, it was possible that the caretaker government could continue on indefinitely.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The situation was similar to that in Bavaria, Saxony, Hesse, Württemberg and Hamburg, although the Reich government did not concern itself with them.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] A center-right government in Prussia consisting of the NSDAP (162 seats) and the Centre Party (67 seats) with a 53% majority was technically possible.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Together with the 31 seats of the nationalist-conservative German National People's Party (DNVP), the coalition would have had as many as 260 of 423 seats.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Reich Chancellor von Papen sought such a coalition, but the NSDAP claimed power for itself alone.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] As a result, Papen considered other possibilities.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The first was to carry out the long-debated Reich reform which would have dissolved or divided Prussia.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Because such a path would have achieved its goal only in the long term, was difficult to accomplish and highly controversial, he favored another option.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] He planned to appoint a Reich commissioner in place of the previous government and to enforce the new order, if necessary with the help of the *Reichswehr*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Reich President Friedrich Ebert of the SPD had issued a Reich execution (*Reichsexekution*) – an intervention against an individual state led by the central government to enforce national law – during 1923's German October.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In the face of Communist Party participation in democratically elected left-wing governments in Saxony and Thuringia, the forcible removal of the governments had been justified by the fact that peace and order were endangered in the two states.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Papen found an analogous justification for Prussia in the clashes culminating in the Altona Bloody Sunday of 17 July 1932 which involved the Nazi SA, which had just had the ban against it lifted by the Papen government, and the Communists and their supporters.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The deadly confrontations and ensuing police action differed markedly from the Reich execution against Saxony in 1923.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Then there had indeed been doubts about the loyalty of Saxony's left-wing government to the constitution and its willingness to take police action, but there was no question of this in Prussia's case.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] By means of the decree Hindenburg authorized the Reich Chancellor to become Reich Commissioner for Prussia and enabled him to remove the caretaker Prussian government from office.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] By not dating the decree, Hindenburg left to Papen the choice of the time at which to make use of the power.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The third option, which would have consisted of waiting and leaving Prussia's caretaker minority government in office and trusting that it would get the situation under control even without a parliamentary majority, was one that Papen from the outset did not consider.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] On 20 July 1932, Prussia's Deputy Minister President Heinrich Hirtsiefer, in place of the acting but ill Minister President Otto Braun, along with Interior Minister Carl Severing and his colleague from the finance department Otto Klepper, went to see Papen at his request.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Papen informed the constitutional ministers about the Hindenburg decree that allowed him to be installed as Reich commissioner and for the caretaker government to be removed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] He said that the step was necessary because it appeared that "public safety and order in Prussia could no longer be guaranteed".
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] A state of emergency was declared with immediate effect, and the Reichswehr minister was appointed as holder of executive power.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Prussia's representatives objected to the coup saying that Prussia had not violated any of its responsibilities under the Reich constitution and its laws, and had done as much for security as the other states even though its jurisdiction included the areas of greatest unrest.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The Braun government therefore challenged the constitutionality of the emergency decree.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Severing responded negatively to Papen's suggestion that he voluntarily relinquish his official duties, saying that he would "yield only to force".
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Otto Klepper reported a year later in an essay in the exile newspaper *The New Journal* that he had hoped that Severing would resist after he made his declaration, especially since both Papen and Interior Minister Wilhelm von Gayl, who was also present, had seemed very uncertain.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] "I suggested that we recess the meeting with Papen for an hour to discuss further action by the Prussian government and went to the door.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] But Severing declared that he had nothing more to discuss with me, and remained seated.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In the afternoon of the same day, Severing, who as interior minister commanded a force of 90,000 Prussian police officers, let himself be led out of his office and ministry by a delegation consisting of the police chief whom Papen had just appointed and two police officers.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Papen had imposed a military state of emergency under the Reichswehr – a national force of 100,000 men – and, after the Prussian government backed down, occupied the Prussian Interior Ministry, the Berlin police headquarters and the headquarters of the *Schutzpolizei* (protective police).
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The Berlin police chief Albert Grzesinski, his deputy Bernhard Weiß, and the commander of the protective police, the *Centre Party* politician Magnus Heimannsberg, were taken into custody and released the next day, after they had bound themselves in writing to engage in no more official acts.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Immediately after the dismissal of the state government, a large-scale purge began.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Numerous officials who had belonged to the previous coalition parties, especially the SPD, were put on temporary retirement and replaced by conservative officials, the majority of them German nationalists.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] This step, in addition to affecting the cabinet of Otto Braun, was directed especially against Social Democratic provincial presidents and leading Social Democrats within police organizations.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Following a decree issued on 12 November 1932, those who had been placed on retirement were either dismissed or delegated to the provinces.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In this way 69 ministerial officials with republican sentiments were sidelined.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In addition to members of the Braun cabinet, they included among others Carl Steinhoff, vice-president of the province of East Prussia, and Carl Freter, district administrator of Calau in Brandenburg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] With targeted interventions against the police, especially the political police, an essential part of the power apparatus in Prussia had already been "cleansed" before Adolf Hitler's chancellorship.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] There was hardly any resistance, mainly because the SPD's executive board had decided on 16 July not to resist with the resources available to it in order to avoid provoking a civil war.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Despite its previous declarations, the Prussian government refused to respond with violence of its own to the violence that the national emergency and emergency decree had officially sanctioned.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Deployment of the Prussian police and the *Reichsbanner Schwarz-Rot-Gold* – an organization formed by three center and left of center parties to defend parliamentary democracy – was rejected.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Even non-violent resistance in the form of a general strike was not considered because it did not seem feasible in view of the high unemployment during the Great Depression.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] There was also little prospect of success in a call for civil disobedience by civil servants.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] If open resistance were to occur, the government anticipated the outbreak of civil war, especially in the event of an armed clash between the Reichswehr and the state police, which it wanted to avoid at all costs.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Moreover, legal recourse had not yet been exhausted.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Joseph Goebbels noted in his diary on 21 July: "The Reds have missed their great hour.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] On 21 July 1932 the Prussian government filed an application for a preliminary injunction and a constitutional complaint with the State Court for the German Reich (*Staatsgerichtshof für das Deutsche Reich*).
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The petitioners included the State of Prussia, represented by Arnold Brecht of the Prussian State Ministry, the parliamentary groups of the Social Democratic Party and the Centre Party in the Prussian Landtag, and also the states of Bavaria and Baden.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] They disputed the constitutionality of the decree on the grounds that Prussia was not ungovernable as presupposed in the decree.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] They therefore applied for a preliminary injunction to prohibit the appointed Reich commissioner from performing his duties.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The application was rejected on 25 July 1932 because the court did not want to anticipate its final decision: in order to declare the emergency decree of the Reich president invalid, reasons would have to be brought forward that were not yet available to the court.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The court stated in addition that a temporary injunction was only to be issued if it appeared necessary to avert substantial harm, but any harm Prussia might incur under the emergency decree could not be proven at the time.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In the stormy and highly publicized oral hearing, Arnold Brecht pointed out in defense of the State of Prussia that the civil war-like conditions in Prussia that led to the emergency decree had been ignited by the lifting of the ban on uniforms and on the SA on 14 June.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The alleged "inner unfreedom" of the Prussian government had not existed, but that of the Reich government in its association with the National Socialists had.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Brecht tried to prove that the Reich government, in agreement with the National Socialists, had purposefully worked towards removing the Prussian government from office with its preceding measures.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In doing so, it had wanted to take the wind out of the National Socialists' sails.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Georg Gottheiner, an administrative lawyer and DNVP member, spoke as the main representative of the Reich government.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] He disputed Brecht's argumentation, saying that there had been no collusion with the National Socialists.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Their "excitement" had built up precisely because of the Party's "one-sided treatment" by the Prussian government.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Prussia had fought National Socialism and favored communism.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The lifting of the SA ban was supposed to serve as an "outlet" for the Nazi's anger.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In its examination of the existence of a significant disturbance or endangerment of public security and order, the State Court found that the government of Prussia was capable of acting and remained able to act assertively.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The court found that the facts of paragraph 2 were present: "If public security and order are seriously disturbed or endangered ..., the president of the Reich may take measures necessary for their restoration, intervening if need be with the assistance of the armed forces" (Article 48).
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The cooperation between the Braun government and the Reich commissioner that was indirectly called for in the judgement was from the outset not possible.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The Reich government overrode the provisions of the judgement and did not intend to return governmental power to the legitimate government after the commissioner's temporary work was completed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The ruling partially justified both sides and preserved the dualism of Prussia and the Reich.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Since the removal of the government was considered illegitimate, the restoration of the government should in fact have been called for.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In the end, the court capitulated to the facts that had been created.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The judgement basically tolerated a breach of the constitution because the court shied away from charging the Reich president with the act.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Historian Michael Stolleis assessed the judgement as a "landmark in the constitutional history describing the downfall of the Republic.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] According to historian Dirk Blasius' account, the verdict was perceived by almost everyone as either a welcome defeat or a clumsy failure of the Reich government.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Only the press that supported the government called for an additional decisive step towards an authoritarian state.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The "political passages" of the judgement were disseminated by most newspapers and prepared the ground for the later popular view that in a time of insecurity and disorder, emergency law had to be used to crack down.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Carl Schmitt, who had represented Papen in the trial along with Erwin Jacobi and Carl Bilfinger, later endorsed the legality of the coup in an expert opinion.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Between the promulgation of the decree and the court ruling, Papen's provisional government replaced Prussia's top administrative and police officials.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The Braun government, rehabilitated in terms of state law but deprived of its real power, convened for its weekly cabinet meetings as a so-called "sovereign government".
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The true power, however, lay with the representatives of the Reich execution – the "Commissar Government" under Franz Bracht.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] It was not until Adolf Hitler seized power in 1933 that Hermann Göring, with Papen's help, secured a new emergency decree from Hindenburg that officially deposed Braun's "sovereign government".
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] His response was again limited to filing a complaint with the State Constitutional Court on 7 February 1933.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Articles 114, 115, 117, 118, 123, 124 and 153 of the Constitution of the German Reich shall be suspended until further notice.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Upon the promulgation of this decree, executive power shall pass to the Reich minister of defense, who may transfer it to military commanders.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] For the implementation of the measures necessary for the restoration of public safety, the entire protective police [*Schutzpolizei*] of the designated area shall be directly subordinated to the holder of executive power.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Whoever causes a common danger to human life by an offence according to para.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 1 shall be punished with imprisonment [*Zuchthaus*], in extenuating circumstances with *Gefängnis* of not less than 6 months and, if the offence causes the loss of human life, with death, in extenuating circumstances with *Zuchthaus* of not less than 2 years.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] In addition, confiscation of property may be imposed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Any person who incites or encourages an offence dangerous to the public (para.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 2) shall be punished by *Zuchthaus*, and in extenuating circumstances by *Gefängnis* for not less than 3 months.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The crimes punishable by life imprisonment under Criminal Code §§ 81 (high treason), 302 (arson), 311 (explosion), 312 (flooding), 315 para.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 2 (damage to railway installations) shall be punishable by death if committed after the enactment of the decree; under the same condition, the death penalty may be imposed in the case of Criminal Code § 92 (treason); likewise in the cases of § 125 para.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 2 (mob ringleaders and those who commit acts of violence as parts of mobs) and § 115 para.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 2 (ringleaders and resisters during riots), if the perpetrator has committed the act of resistance by force or threat with weapons or in a conscious and deliberate encounter with armed persons.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] Upon request of the holder of executive power, extraordinary courts shall be established by the Reich minister of justice.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] The jurisdiction of these courts shall include, in addition to the offences listed in § 9 of the Decree of the president of the Reich of 29 March 1921 (Reich Law Gazette. p.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] 371), the misdemeanors and felonies under § 3 of this decree.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] This Decree shall enter into force upon enactment.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] *Zuchthaus* was the most severe form of punishment and included stricter confinement and compulsory work for the inmates.
[src:adam-stegerwald/1932-prussian-coup-d-état] It was also considered to be dishonoring.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The **20 July plot**, sometimes referred to as **Operation Valkyrie** (German: *Unternehmen Walküre*), was a failed attempt to assassinate Adolf Hitler, the dictator of Nazi Germany, and overthrow the Nazi government on 20 July 1944.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The plotters were part of the German resistance, mainly composed of *Wehrmacht* officers.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The principal mastermind of the conspiracy, Claus von Stauffenberg, tried to kill Hitler by detonating an explosive hidden in a briefcase.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] However, due to the location of the bomb at the time of detonation, the blast only dealt Hitler minor injuries.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The planners' subsequent *coup* attempt also failed and resulted in a purge of the *Wehrmacht*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] As early as 1938, German military officers had plotted to overthrow Hitler, but indecisive leadership and the pace of global events stymied action.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Plotters gained a sense of urgency in 1943 after Germany lost the Battle of Stalingrad and Soviet forces began to push towards Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Under the leadership of Stauffenberg, plotters tried to assassinate Hitler at least five times in 1943 and 1944.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] With the Nazi secret police, the Gestapo, closing in on the plotters, a final attempt was organised in July 1944.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg personally took a briefcase containing a block of plastic explosive to a conference in the Wolf's Lair.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The explosives were armed and placed next to Hitler, but it appears they were moved unwittingly at the last moment behind a table leg by Heinz Brandt, inadvertently saving Hitler's life.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] When the bomb detonated, it killed Brandt and two others, while the rest of the room's occupants were injured, one of whom, Rudolf Schmundt, later died from his injuries.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler's trousers were singed by the blast, and he suffered a perforated eardrum and conjunctivitis, but was otherwise unharmed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The plotters, unaware of their failure, then attempted a *coup d'état*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] A few hours after the blast, the conspiracy used *Wehrmacht* units to take control of several cities, including Berlin, immediately after giving them disinformation on the intention of the orders they were given.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] This part of the coup d'état attempt is referred to by the name "Operation Valkyrie", which has also become associated with the entire event.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Within hours, the Nazi regime had reasserted its control of Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] A few members of the conspiracy, including Stauffenberg, were executed by firing squad the same night.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In the months after the *coup* attempt, the Gestapo arrested more than 7,000 people, 4,980 of whom were executed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The apparent aim of the coup d'état attempt was to wrest political control of Germany and its armed forces from the Nazi Party (including the Schutzstaffel) and to make peace with the Western Allies as soon as possible.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The details of the conspirators' peace initiatives remain unknown.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Since 1938 there had been groups plotting an overthrow of some kind within the German Army and in the German Military Intelligence Organization.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] They soon established contacts with several prominent civilians, including Carl Goerdeler, the former mayor of Leipzig, and Helmuth James von Moltke, the great-grandnephew of Moltke the Elder, hero of the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Groups of military plotters exchanged ideas with civilian, political, and intellectual resistance groups in the Kreisauer Kreis (which met at the von Moltke estate in Kreisau) and in other secret circles.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Moltke was against killing Hitler; instead, he wanted him placed on trial.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Moltke said, "we are all amateurs and would only bungle it".
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Moltke also believed killing Hitler would be hypocritical: Hitler and National Socialism had turned wrongdoing into a system, something which the resistance should avoid.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In 1942 a new conspiratorial group formed, led by Colonel Henning von Tresckow, a member of Field Marshal Fedor von Bock's staff, who commanded Army Group Centre in Operation Barbarossa.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Tresckow systematically recruited oppositionists into the Group's staff, making it the nerve centre of the army resistance.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Little could be done against Hitler as he was heavily guarded, and none of the plotters could get near enough to him.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] During 1942, Oster and Tresckow nevertheless succeeded in rebuilding an effective resistance network.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Their most important recruit was General Friedrich Olbricht, head of the General Army Office headquarters at the Bendlerblock in central Berlin, who controlled an independent system of communications to reserve units throughout Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Linking this asset to Tresckow's resistance group in Army Group Centre created a viable coup apparatus.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In late 1942 Tresckow and Olbricht formulated a plan to assassinate Hitler and stage an overthrow during Hitler's visit to the headquarters of Army Group Centre at Smolensk in March 1943, by placing a bomb on his plane (Operation Spark).
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The bomb failed to detonate, and a second attempt a week later with Hitler at an exhibition of captured Soviet weaponry in Berlin also failed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] These failures demoralised the conspirators.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] During 1943 Tresckow tried without success to recruit senior army field commanders such as Field Marshal Erich von Manstein and Field Marshal Gerd von Rundstedt, to support a seizure of power.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Tresckow, in particular, worked on his Commander-in-Chief of Army Group Centre, Field Marshal Günther von Kluge, to persuade him to move against Hitler and at times succeeded in gaining his consent, only to find him indecisive at the last minute.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] However, despite their refusals, none of the Field Marshals reported their treasonous activities to the Gestapo or Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] While the primary goal of the plotters was to remove Hitler from power, they did so for various reasons.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The majority of the group behind the 20 July plot were conservative nationalists—idealists, but not necessarily of a democratic stripe.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Martin Borschat portrays their motivations as a matter of aristocratic resentment, writing that the plot was mainly carried out by conservative elites who were initially integrated by the Nazi government but during the war lost their influence and were concerned about regaining it.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] However, at least in Stauffenberg's case, the conviction that Nazi Germany's atrocities against civilians and prisoners of war were a dishonour to the nation and its military was likely a major motivating factor.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Historian Judith Michel assesses the circle around the 20 July Group as a diverse and heterogeneous group that included liberal democrats, conservatives, social democrats, authoritarian aristocrats, and even communists.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The common goal was to overthrow Hitler's regime and bring the war to a swift end.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] There is evidence of the plot encompassing a broad spectrum of plotters which included communists.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] That April, before the attempted coup, Stauffenberg agreed to cooperate with the Operational Leadership of the KPD (Communist Party of Germany) remaining in Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Contacts were established through the Social Democrats Adolf Reichwein and Julius Leber.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Among demands initially countenanced by the plotters for issue towards the Allies were such points as re-establishment of Germany's 1914 boundaries with Belgium, France and Poland and no reparations.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] They believed that Europe should be controlled under German hegemony.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The overall goals towards Poland were mixed within the plotters.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Most of the plotters found it desirable to restore the old German borders of 1914, while others pointed out that the demands were unrealistic, and amendments had to be made.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Some like Friedrich-Werner Graf von der Schulenburg even wanted all of Poland annexed to Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] To Poland, which was fighting against Nazi Germany with both its army and government in exile, the territorial demands and traditional nationalistic visions of resistance were not much different from the racist policies of Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg, one of the leaders of the plot, stated in 1939 during the Poland campaign, five years before the *coup* attempt: "It is essential that we begin a systemic colonisation in Poland.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Many members of the plot had helped the Nazis to gain power and shared revisionist foreign policy goals pursued by Hitler, and even at the time of the plot were anti-democratic, hoping to replace Hitler with a conservative-authoritarian government involving aristocratic rule.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] They opposed popular legitimation or mass participation in governance of the state.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Commencement of peace negotiations with the Western Allies, punishment of those Germans responsible for the Second World War.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] By mid-1943 the tide of war was turning decisively against Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The army plotters and their civilian allies became convinced that Hitler should be assassinated, so that a government acceptable to the western Allies could be formed, and a separate peace negotiated in time to prevent a Soviet invasion of Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In August 1943 Tresckow met, for the first time, a young staff officer named Lieutenant Colonel Claus von Stauffenberg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Severely wounded in North Africa, Stauffenberg was a political conservative and zealous German nationalist.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] From early 1942, he had come to share two basic convictions with many military officers: that Germany was being led to disaster and that Hitler's removal from power was necessary.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] After the Battle of Stalingrad in December 1942, despite his religious scruples, he concluded that the Führer's assassination was a lesser moral evil than Hitler's remaining in power.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg brought a new tone of decisiveness to the ranks of the resistance movement.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] When Tresckow was assigned to the Eastern Front, Stauffenberg took charge of planning and executing the assassination attempt.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Olbricht now put forward a new strategy for staging a coup against Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Olbricht suggested that this plan could be used to mobilise the Reserve Army for the purpose of the coup.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In August and September 1943, Tresckow drafted the "revised" Valkyrie plan and new supplementary orders.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] A secret declaration began with these words: "The Führer Adolf Hitler is dead!
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Previously, it was believed that Stauffenberg was mainly responsible for the Valkyrie plan, but documents recovered by the Soviet Union after the war and released in 2007 suggest that the plan was developed by Tresckow by late 1943.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] All written information was handled by Tresckow's wife, Erika, and by Margarethe von Oven, his secretary.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Both women wore gloves to avoid leaving fingerprints.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] On at least two other occasions Tresckow had tried to assassinate the Führer.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The first plan was to shoot him during dinner at the army base camp, but this plan was aborted because it was widely believed that Hitler wore a bullet-proof vest.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators also considered poisoning him, but this was not possible because his food was specially prepared and tasted.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] They concluded that a time bomb was the only option.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Operation Valkyrie could only be put into effect by Hitler himself, or by General Friedrich Fromm, commander of the Reserve Army, so the latter had to be either won over to the conspiracy or in some way neutralised if the plan was to succeed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] As the war situation deteriorated, Hitler no longer appeared in public and rarely visited Berlin.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He spent most of his time at his headquarters at the *Wolfsschanze* near Rastenburg in East Prussia, with occasional breaks at his Bavarian mountain retreat Obersalzberg near Berchtesgaden.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In both places, he was heavily guarded and rarely saw people he did not know or trust.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Himmler and the *Gestapo* were increasingly suspicious of plots against Hitler and rightly suspected the officers of the General Staff, which was indeed the source of many conspiracies against him.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] By mid-1944 the *Gestapo* was closing in on the conspirators.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Even if it fails, we must take action in Berlin ⁠,⁠ ⁠for the practical purpose no longer matters; what matters now is that the German resistance movement must take the plunge before the eyes of the world and of history.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Nothing came of this meeting, but Popitz was not arrested and Himmler apparently did nothing to track down the resistance network which he knew was operating within the state bureaucracy.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] It is possible that Himmler, who by late 1943 knew that the war was unwinnable, allowed the plot to go ahead in the knowledge that if it succeeded he would be Hitler's successor, and could then bring about a peace settlement.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Popitz was not alone in seeing Himmler as a potential ally.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] General von Bock advised Tresckow to seek his support, but there is no evidence that he did so.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Goerdeler was apparently also in indirect contact with Himmler via a mutual acquaintance, Carl Langbehn.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Wilhelm Canaris's biographer Heinz Höhne suggests that Canaris and Himmler were working together to bring about a change of regime, but this remains speculation.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] On Saturday 1 July 1944 Stauffenberg was appointed Chief of Staff to General Friedrich Fromm at the Reserve Army headquarters on Bendlerstraße in central Berlin.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] This position enabled Stauffenberg to attend Hitler's military conferences, either at the *Wolfsschanze* in East Prussia or at Berchtesgaden, and would thus give him an opportunity, perhaps the last that would present itself, to kill Hitler with a bomb or a pistol.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Meanwhile, new key allies had been gained.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] These included General Carl-Heinrich von Stülpnagel, the German military commander in France, who would take control in Paris when Hitler was killed, and it was hoped, negotiate an immediate armistice with the invading Allied armies.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] On 7 July 1944 General Helmuth Stieff was to kill Hitler at a display of new uniforms at Klessheim castle near Salzburg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] However, Stieff felt unable to kill Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg now decided to do both, assassinate Hitler and to manage the plot in Berlin.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In fact, it was unusual for Himmler to attend military conferences.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] By 15 July, when Stauffenberg again flew to the *Wolfsschanze*, this condition had been dropped.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The plan was for Stauffenberg to plant the briefcase with the bomb in Hitler's conference room with a timer running, excuse himself from the meeting, wait for the explosion, then fly back to Berlin and join the other plotters at the Bendlerblock.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Operation Valkyrie would be mobilised, the Reserve Army would take control of Germany and the other Nazi leaders would be arrested.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Beck would be appointed provisional head of state, Goerdeler would be chancellor, and Witzleben would be commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Again on 15 July, the attempt was called off at the last minute.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Himmler and Göring were present, but Hitler was called out of the room at the last moment.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg was able to intercept the bomb and prevent its discovery.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] On the morning of Thursday 20 July Stauffenberg flew back to the *Wolfsschanze* for another military conference at which Hitler would be present, once again with a bomb in his briefcase.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At around 12:30 pm as the conference began, Stauffenberg asked to use a washroom in Wilhelm Keitel's office, saying that he had to change his shirt, which indeed was soaked through with sweat, it being a very hot day.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] There, assisted by von Haeften, he used pliers to crush the end of a pencil detonator inserted into a 1 kilogram (2.2 lb) block of plastic explosive wrapped in brown paper, that was prepared by Wessel von Freytag-Loringhoven.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The pencil detonator consisted of a thin copper tube containing cupric chloride that would take about ten minutes to silently eat through wire holding back the firing pin from the percussion cap.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] It was slow going due to war wounds that had cost Stauffenberg an eye, his right hand, and two fingers on his left hand.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Interrupted by a guard knocking on the door advising him that the meeting was about to begin, he was not able to prime the second bomb, which he gave to his aide-de-camp, Werner von Haeften.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg placed the single primed bomb inside his briefcase and, with the unwitting assistance of Major Ernst John von Freyend, entered the conference room containing Hitler and 20 officers, positioning the briefcase under the table near Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] After a few minutes, Stauffenberg received a planned telephone call and left the room.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At 12:42 the bomb detonated, demolishing the conference room and killing a stenographer instantly.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] More than 20 people in the room were injured with three officers later dying.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler survived, as did everyone else who was shielded from the blast by the conference table leg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] His trousers were singed and tattered, and he suffered from a perforated eardrum (as did most of the other 24 people in the room), as well as from conjunctivitis in his right eye.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler's personal physician, Theodor Morell, administered penicillin which had been taken from captured Allied soldiers for treatment; Morell had previously observed the death of Reinhard Heydrich from sepsis in an assassination two years earlier.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg was seen leaving the conference building by Kurt Salterberg, a soldier on guard duty who did not consider this out of the ordinary as attendees sometimes left to collect documents.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He then saw a "massive" cloud of smoke, wood splinters and paper and men being hurled through a window and door.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg, upon witnessing the explosion and smoke, assumed that Hitler was dead.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He then climbed into a staff car with his aide Werner von Haeften and managed to bluff his way past three checkpoints to exit the *Wolfsschanze* complex.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Haeften then tossed the second (unprimed) bomb into the forest as they made a dash for Rastenburg airfield, reaching it before it could be realised that Stauffenberg could be responsible for the explosion.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At first it was thought that the explosion had been the result of an aerial bombing, but when it was confirmed that no warplanes had flown over and Stauffenberg was absent, the theory of an assassination attempt gained strength.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] By 13:00 he was airborne in a Heinkel He 111 arranged by General Eduard Wagner.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] By the time Stauffenberg's aircraft reached Berlin about 16:00, General Erich Fellgiebel, an officer at the *Wolfsschanze* who was in on the plot, had phoned the Bendlerblock and told the plotters that Hitler had survived the explosion.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] As a result, the plot to mobilise Operation Valkyrie would have no chance of succeeding once the officers of the Reserve Army knew that Hitler was alive.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] There was more confusion when Stauffenberg's aircraft landed and he phoned from the airport to say that Hitler *was* in fact dead.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The Bendlerblock plotters did not know whom to believe.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Finally, at 16:00 Olbricht issued the orders for Operation Valkyrie to be mobilised.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The vacillating General Fromm, however, phoned Field Marshal Wilhelm Keitel at the Wolf's Lair and was assured that Hitler was alive.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Keitel demanded to know Stauffenberg's whereabouts.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] This told Fromm that the plot had been traced to his headquarters and that he was in mortal danger.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm replied that he thought Stauffenberg was with Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Meanwhile, General Carl-Heinrich von Stülpnagel, military governor of occupied France, managed to disarm the SD and SS and captured most of their leadership.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He travelled to Field Marshal Günther von Kluge's headquarters and asked him to contact the Allies, only to be informed that Hitler was alive.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At 16:40 Stauffenberg and Haeften arrived at the Bendlerblock.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm, presumably to protect himself, changed sides and attempted to have Stauffenberg arrested.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Olbricht and Stauffenberg restrained him at gunpoint and Olbricht then appointed General Erich Hoepner to take over his duties.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] By this time Himmler had taken charge of the situation and had issued orders countermanding Olbricht's mobilisation of Operation Valkyrie.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In many places the coup was going ahead, led by officers who believed that Hitler was dead.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] City Commandant, and conspirator, Lieutenant General Paul von Hase ordered the *Wachbataillon Großdeutschland*, under the command of Major Otto Ernst Remer, to secure the Wilhelmstraße and arrest Propaganda Minister Joseph Goebbels.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In Vienna, Prague, and many other places troops occupied Nazi Party offices and arrested Gauleiters and SS officers.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At around 18:10, the commander of Military District III (Berlin), General Joachim von Kortzfleisch, was summoned to the Bendlerblock; he angrily refused Olbricht's orders, kept shouting "the Führer is alive", was arrested, and held under guard.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] General Karl Freiherr von Thüngen was appointed in his place but proved to be of almost no help.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] General Fritz Lindemann, who was supposed to make a proclamation to the German people over the radio, failed to appear and as he held the only copy, Beck had to work on a new one.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At 19:00 Hitler was sufficiently recovered to make phone calls.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He called Goebbels at the Propaganda Ministry.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Goebbels arranged for Hitler to speak to Major Otto Ernst Remer, commander of the troops surrounding the Ministry.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] After assuring him that he was still alive, Hitler ordered Remer to regain control of the situation in Berlin and capture the conspirators alive.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Major Remer ordered his troops to surround and seal off the Bendlerblock, but not to enter the buildings.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At 20:00 a furious Witzleben arrived at the Bendlerblock and had a bitter argument with Stauffenberg, who was still insisting that the coup could go ahead.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At around this time the planned seizure of power in Paris was aborted when Field Marshal Günther von Kluge, who had recently been appointed commander-in-chief in the West, learnt that Hitler was alive.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] As Remer regained control of the city and word spread that Hitler was still alive, the less resolute members of the conspiracy in Berlin began to change sides.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm was freed from his room and fighting broke out in the Bendlerblock between officers supporting and opposing the coup; Stauffenberg was wounded after a shootout.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] As the fighting was still ongoing, Remer and his forces arrived at the Bendlerblock and the conspirators were overwhelmed and arrested; by 23:00 Fromm and Remer had regained control of the building.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] At first Beck only seriously wounded himself—he was then shot in the neck and killed by soldiers.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Despite protests from Remer (who had been ordered by Hitler to arrest the conspirators), at 00:10 on 21 July the four officers were executed in the courtyard outside, possibly to prevent them from revealing Fromm's involvement.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Others would have been executed as well, but at 00:30 *Waffen-SS* personnel led by SS-*Obersturmbannführer* Otto Skorzeny arrived and further executions were forbidden.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Over the following weeks, Himmler's *Gestapo*, driven by a furious Hitler, rounded up nearly everyone who had the remotest connection with the plot.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The discovery of letters and diaries in the homes and offices of those arrested revealed the plots of 1938, 1939, and 1943, and this led to further rounds of arrests, including that of Colonel General Franz Halder, who finished the war in a concentration camp.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Under Himmler's new *Sippenhaft* (blood guilt) laws, many relatives of the principal plotters were also arrested in the immediate aftermath of the failed plot.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Particularly noteworthy in considering this issue is the scientific publication of Robert Loeffel.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In his study, Loeffel came to the conclusion that *Sippenhaft*, as part of state terror at the end of the war, was a means of intimidation within Nazi Germany, when in reality this practice was not always applied, and most of the terror was adopted only after 20 July.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] This was due to its duality: terror was implemented only in quantities necessary to maintain a level of fear among the population that would not lead them to go over to the side of resistance.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] More than 7,000 people were arrested and 4,980 were executed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Not all of them were connected with the plot, since the *Gestapo* used the occasion to settle scores with many other people suspected of opposition sympathies.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Allied radio stations also speculated on who the possible remaining suspects could be, many of whom were eventually implicated in the plot.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Very few of the plotters tried to escape or to deny their guilt when arrested.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Those who survived interrogation were given perfunctory trials before the People's Court, a kangaroo court that always decided in favour of the prosecution.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The court's president, Roland Freisler, was a fanatical Nazi seen shouting furiously and insulting the accused in the trial, which was filmed for propaganda purposes.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The plotters were stripped of their uniforms and given old, shabby clothing to humiliate them for the cameras.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The officers involved in the plot were "tried" before the Court of Military Honour, a drumhead court-martial that merely considered the evidence furnished to it by the *Gestapo* before expelling the accused from the Army in disgrace and handing them over to the People's Court.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The first trials were held on 7 and 8 August 1944 and were held in the plenary chamber of the Berlin high court the Kammergericht in Schöneberg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler had ordered that those found guilty should be "hanged like cattle".
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Many people took their own lives prior to either their trial or their execution, including Kluge, who was accused of having knowledge of the plot beforehand and not revealing it to Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Stülpnagel tried to commit suicide, but survived and was hanged.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Tresckow killed himself the day after the failed plot by use of a hand grenade in no man's land between Soviet and German lines.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm's attempt to win favour by executing Stauffenberg and others on the night of 20 July had merely exposed his own previous lack of action and apparent failure to report the plot.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Having been arrested on 21 July, Fromm was later convicted and sentenced to death by the People's Court.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Despite his knowledge of the conspiracy, his formal sentence charged him with poor performance in his duties.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He was executed in Brandenburg an der Havel.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler personally commuted his death sentence from hanging to the "more honourable" firing squad.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Erwin Planck, the son of the physicist Max Planck, was executed for his involvement.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] A report of SS-*Obergruppenführer* Ernst Kaltenbrunner to Hitler dated 29 November 1944 on the background of the plot states that the Pope was somehow a conspirator, specifically naming Eugenio Pacelli, Pope Pius XII, as being a party in the attempt.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] A member of the SA convicted of participating in the plot was SA-*Obergruppenführer* Wolf-Heinrich Graf von Helldorf, who was the *Orpo* Police Chief of Berlin and had been in contact with members of the resistance since before the war.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Collaborating closely with SS-*Gruppenführer* Arthur Nebe, he was supposed to direct all police forces in Berlin to stand down and not interfere in the military actions to seize the government.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] However, his actions on 20 July had minimal influence on the events.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] For his involvement in the conspiracy, he was later arrested, convicted of treason and executed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] After 3 February 1945, when Freisler was killed in an American air raid, there were no more formal trials, but as late as April, with the war weeks away from its end, Canaris' diary was found, and many more people were implicated.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hans Von Dohnanyi was accused of being the "spiritual leader" of the conspiracy to assassinate Hitler, and executed on 6 April 1945.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Dietrich Bonhoeffer, whom Von Dohnanyi had recruited into the Abwehr, was executed 9 April 1945 along with Canaris, Oster, and four others.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Executions continued and ramped up into the last days of the war, as the Nazis were determined to take down as many of their enemies with them as they possibly could.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler took his survival to be a "divine moment in history", and commissioned a special decoration to be made for each person wounded or killed in the blast.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The result was the Wound Badge of 20 July 1944.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The badges were struck in three values: gold, silver, and black.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] (The colours denoted the severity of the wounds received by each recipient.) A total of 100 badges were manufactured, and 47 are believed to have actually been awarded.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Each badge was accompanied by an ornate award document personally signed by Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The badges themselves bore a facsimile of his signature, making them among the rarest decorations to have been awarded by Nazi Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] For his role in stopping the coup Major Remer was promoted to colonel and ended the war as a Major General.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] After the war he co-founded the Socialist Reich Party and remained a prominent neo-Nazi and advocate of Holocaust denial until his death in 1997.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Major Philipp von Boeselager, the German officer who provided the plastic explosives used in the bomb, escaped detection and survived the war.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He was the second-to-last survivor of those involved in the plot and died on 1 May 2008, aged 90.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The last survivor of the 20 July Plot was *Oberleutnant* Ewald-Heinrich von Kleist-Schmenzin, the thwarted plotter of just a few months before.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators had earlier designated positions in secret to form a government that would take office after the assassination of Hitler were it to prove successful.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Because of the plot's failure, such a government never rose to power and most of its members were executed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Also, Andreas Hermes became chairman of the food committee in the Bizonal Economic Council after the war, but this was a role analogous to a parliamentary committee chairman rather than a government minister.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] It was planned to include one Austrian politician (probably Heinrich Gleißner or Karl Seitz) as minister without portfolio to keep Austria in the Reich.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Albert Speer was listed in several notes of the conspirators as a possible Minister of Armaments; however, most of these notes stated Speer should not be approached until after Hitler was dead and one conjectural government chart had a question mark beside Speer's name.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] This (in addition to Speer being one of Hitler's closest and most trusted friends) most likely saved Speer from arrest by the SS.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Wilhelm, Crown Prince of Germany, was also under suspicion as he was touted to be head of state after Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He was placed under the supervision of the *Gestapo* and his home in the Cecilienhof at Potsdam watched.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The extent of Generalfeldmarschall Erwin Rommel's involvement in the military's resistance against Hitler or the 20 July plot is difficult to ascertain, as most of the leaders who were directly involved did not survive and limited documentation on the conspirators' plans and preparations exists.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Historians' opinions on this matter vary greatly.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] According to Peter Hoffmann, he had turned into Hitler's resolute opponent and in the end supported the coup (though not the assassination itself).
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He was even the natural leader of the opposition in France to some extent, considering the fact he had drawn many military and political personnel into his orbit in preparation of a "Western solution".
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Ralf Georg Reuth thinks that the conspirators perhaps mistook Rommel's ambiguous attitude for approval of the assassination.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] In this regard, it should be remembered that the conspirators normally did not explicitly mention the assassination.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel for his part was in fact both very naive and very attached to Hitler (who was the personification of National Socialism, which had provided Rommel with a great career).
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Thus even if Caesar von Hofacker—personal advisor to Stülpnagel— had mentioned a violent upheaval in Berlin, Rommel would perhaps not have interpreted it as an assassination.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Thus, Rommel's participation remains ambiguous and the perception of it largely has its source in the subsequent events (especially Rommel's forced suicide) and the accounts by surviving participants.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] According to a post-war account by Karl Strölin, the *Oberbürgermeister* of Stuttgart at that time, he and two other conspirators, Alexander von Falkenhausen and Carl Heinrich von Stülpnagel began efforts to bring Rommel into the anti-Hitler conspiracy in early 1944.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] On 15 April 1944 Rommel's new chief of staff, Hans Speidel, arrived in Normandy and reintroduced Rommel to Stülpnagel.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Speidel had previously been connected to Carl Goerdeler, the civilian leader of the resistance, but not to the plotters led by Stauffenberg, and only came to the attention of Stauffenberg due to his appointment to Rommel's headquarters.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators felt they needed the support of a field marshal on active duty.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Witzleben was a field marshal, but had not been on active duty since 1942.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators gave instructions to Speidel to bring Rommel into their circle.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Speidel met with the former foreign minister Konstantin von Neurath and Strölin on 27 May in Germany, ostensibly at Rommel's request, although the latter was not present.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Neurath and Strölin suggested opening immediate surrender negotiations in the West, and, according to Speidel, Rommel agreed to further discussions and preparations.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Around the same timeframe, however, the plotters in Berlin were not aware that Rommel had reportedly decided to take part in the conspiracy.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] On 16 May, they informed Allen Dulles, through whom they hoped to negotiate with the Western Allies, that Rommel could not be counted on for support.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Three days before the assassination attempt, on 17 July, Rommel's staff car was strafed by an Allied aircraft in France; he was hospitalised with major injuries and incapacitated on 20 July.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] After the war, his widow maintained that he believed an assassination attempt would spark a civil war.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] According to the journalist and author William L.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Shirer, Rommel knew about the conspiracy and advocated that Hitler be arrested and placed on trial.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Evans concluded that he knew of a plot, but was not involved.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] What is not debated are the results of the failed bomb plot of 20 July.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Many conspirators were arrested and the dragnet expanded to thousands.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Consequently, it did not take long for Rommel to come under suspicion.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He was primarily implicated through his connection to Kluge.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel's name also came up in confessions made under torture by Stülpnagel and Hofacker, and was included in Goerdeler's papers on a list of potential supporters.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hofacker confessed that Rommel had agreed to demand for Hitler to step down, and if he refused, Rommel would join the other conspirators in deposing Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel was also planned to become a member of the post-Hitler government in papers drawn up by Goerdeler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler knew it would cause a major scandal on the home front to have the popular Rommel publicly branded as a traitor.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] With this in mind, he opted to give Rommel the option of suicide via cyanide or a public trial by Freisler's People's Court.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel was well aware that being hauled before the People's Court was tantamount to a death sentence.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He also knew that if he chose to stand trial, his family would have been severely punished even before the all-but-certain conviction and execution.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] With this in mind, he committed suicide on 14 October 1944.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p01] He was buried with full military honours and his family was spared from persecution; his cause of death did not come to light until after the war.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] Involvement of the plotters in war crimes and atrocities has been studied by historians such as Christian Gerlach.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] Gerlach proved that plotters such as Tresckow and Gersdorff were aware of mass murder happening in the East from at least 1941.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] Tresckow also "signed orders for the deportation of thousands of orphaned children for forced labor in the Reich"—the so-called *Heu-Aktion*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] Such actions led historians to question the motives of the plotters, which seemed more concerned with the military situation than with Nazi atrocities and German war crimes.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] However some others assert that, in such actions, Tresckow had to act out of principle to continue with his coup plans.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] Gerlach pointed out that the plotters had "selective moral criteria" and while they were concerned about Jews being exterminated in the Holocaust, they were far less disturbed about mass murder of civilians in the East.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] To Gerlach, the primary motivation of the plotters was to ensure German victory in the war or at least prevent defeat.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] Gerlach's arguments were later supported by the historian Hans Mommsen, who stated that the plotters were interested above all in military victory.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] However, Gerlach's arguments were also criticised by some scholars, among them Peter Hoffmann from McGill University and Klaus Jochen Arnold from the Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] While acknowledging that Tresckow and other 20 July conspirators had been involved in war crimes, Arnold writes that Gerlach's argument is oversimplified.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] In 2011 Danny Orbach, a Harvard University-based historian, wrote that Gerlach's reading of the sources is highly skewed, and, at times, diametrically opposed to what they actually say.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] In one case, according to Orbach, Gerlach had falsely paraphrased the memoir of the resistance fighter Colonel Rudolf Christoph Freiherr von Gersdorff, and in another case, quoted misleadingly from an SS document.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] The "first official memorial service for the resistance fighters of 20 July" was held on the tenth anniversary in 1954.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] The first all-German commemoration of the event did not take place until 1990.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] In 2013 the last surviving member of the plot, Ewald-Heinrich von Kleist-Schmenzin, died in Munich.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] As of 2014, the resistance fighters are generally considered heroes in Germany, according to *Deutsche Welle*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] In 1989, American Gothic Rock band Christian Death released a song entitled ”Nazi Killer” about this assassination attempt.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20-july-plot-p02] The song was featured on their album All the Love All the Hate (Part Two: All the Hate).
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:adam-stegerwald/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] Ladenberg was the son of the Prussian Minister of State Philipp von Ladenberg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] After initially receiving his education from tutors, he attended the Friedrich-Wilhelms-Gymnasium in Berlin and at age 17 joined the Dragoon Guards Regiment for a year.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] In 1816 he left the military as a Lieutenant and studied Law and cameralism in Berlin, Heidelberg und Göttingen.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] After successfully completing his studies he received a place as a law clerk in 1818 in the Prussian civil service.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] From 1824, his career led him from the post of *Regierungsrat* and legal advisor in Cologne to that of *Oberregierungsrat* 1829 in Königsberg und Merseburg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] He was then made "regional president" (*Regierungspräsident*) in Trier in 1834, and six years later Karl vom Stein zum Altenstein appointed him to the ministry for education and cultural affairs and as member of the Prussian Council of State in Berlin.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] When Altenstein died on 14 May 1840, Ladenberg was entrusted with the latter's political responsibilities in a provisional capacity until 8 October.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] From the 22 October he took up this position permanently and from that day onwards led the department for religious Protestant, education and health affairs in the ministry of Johann Albrecht Friedrich von Eichhorn.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] In 1841 he also received the role of extraordinary government commissioner at the Humboldt University of Berlin.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] When Eichhorn resigned all his posts due to the political consequences of the Revolutions of 1848, Ladenberg led the ministry, also under the ministers Maximilian von Schwerin-Putzar and Johann Karl Rodbertus, who held office very briefly.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] From July to November 1848 this was an interim appointment, which was then made permanent.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] Amongst other things, Ladenberg was significantly involved with various reforms: establishment of the Protestant *Oberkirchenrat* (a senior administrative body of the church), preparation of an education law and a health law as well as managing a reorganisation of the art establishment.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] Through the Punctation of Olmütz of 29 November 1850, Ladenberg felt compelled to resign, but neglected to do so in order to see through certain legislation.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] From 9 November to 12 December 1850, Ladenberg was made interim Prime Minister.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adalbert-von-ladenberg] He was later made a *Wirklicher Geheimer Rat* and as such took over the management of the financial authority.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald was born the son of a farmer in Greußenheim in Lower Franconia and attended primary school there between 1881 and 1888 before completing an apprenticeship as a carpenter in Würzburg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] From 1900 to 1902, Stegerwald studied economics under Lujo Brentano at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He began his engagement with the labour movement in 1893, when he joined the Catholic *Gesellenverein*, a non-union Catholic labour society, in Günzburg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] From 1896, he was part of the workers' electoral association of the Centre Party in Munich, where he was committed to building the burgeoning Catholic trade union movement.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He advanced quickly, becoming honorary chairman of the Central Union of Christian Woodworkers in 1899 and, in 1903, general-secretary of the General Association of German Christian Trade Unions, a position he retained until 1929.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In his political role, he steered a conservative course, supporting the Empire and its colonial ambitions.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He attempted to unify the non-socialist unions, such as the Protestant DHV and the Catholic *Gesellvereine*, into a unified organisation to create a counterweight to the socialist free trade unions, though he was unsuccessful.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He supported the German war effort in the First World War and served on the board of the Wartime Food Office from 1916 to 1919, as well as in the Prussian House of Lords during the final year of the war.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In the aftermath of the November Revolution, Stegerwald represented the Catholic trade unions in co-signing the 15 November working agreement between the unions and employers' associations.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] The working agreement set out a common understanding between labour and capital, acknowledging unions as the legitimate representatives of the workers and setting out the basis for collective bargaining agreements and the eight-hour day.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Throughout the following year Stegerwald called for the end to the workers' council movement which was popular among many radical workers, mostly in the socialist unions.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In 1919, he became head of the German Trade Union Federation (DGB), the reorganised Christian trade union federation.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Initially, it bore a close resemblance to Stegerwald's prewar proposal of a broad non-socialist union federation, including the Catholic unions as well as the liberal Hirsch-Duncker unions and the Protestant white-collar associations.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] However, the more secular Hirsch-Duncker unions departed in November, leaving the DGB largely dominated by the Catholic unions with a deeply conservative Protestant minority in the German National Association of Commercial Employees (DHV).
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] As leader of the DGB, Stegerwald struggled to maintain the unity of the federation's conflicting parts.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Left-wing elements such as the Catholic miners' and industrial unions resented Stegerwald's conservative orientation and his continuous attempts to find common cause with conservative Protestants rather than seek better conditions for workers.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] At the same time, he sought constantly to appease the ultraconservative white-collar DHV.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In 1927, he sided with the DGB's industrial unions in opposing a widely-agreed wage increase for civil servants.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] This effort failed and alienated him from the white-collar elements of the DGB, to whom he had previously been a stalwart ally.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] After becoming chair of the Centre's Reichstag delegation in January 1929, he resigned from his union positions.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He was succeeded as chair of the DGB by Heinrich Imbusch, leader of the miners' union.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald was elected to both the national and Prussian constituent assembles early in 1919, and became minister for public welfare in Prussia under Social Democratic minister-president Paul Hirsch.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] At the DGB congress in 1920, Stegerwald proposed the formation of an inter-denominational "People's Party", through which he hoped to unite both Catholics and Protestants in a conservative project opposed to socialism, liberalism, and materialism.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] The idea was roundly rejected: the right wing of the Centre opposed abandoning their Catholic orientation while the left-wing feared the conservative, anti-labour orientation of such a party.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Nonetheless, Stegerwald remained a convinced advocate of a pan-Christian party for the rest of his life.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] During the government impasse following the 1921 Prussian state election, the state Centre Party drafted Stegerwald to serve as interim Minister-President.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He was tasked with putting together a cabinet including Social Democrats, the Centre, the left-liberal Democrats, and the conservative German People's Party.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He was invested by the Landtag with a large majority in April, but soon came to blows with the Social Democrats, who withdrew their support.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] His cabinet consisted of a minority government of the Centre and Democrats, and negotiations to expand it stalled out toward the end of the year.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] It finally collapsed in October when the Democrats quit in protest against Stegerwald's proposal to hand the interior ministry to the Social Democrats.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He resigned, and in short order a new centre-left government was formed under Social Democrat Otto Braun.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] This proved to be the end of Stegerwald's involvement in Prussian state politics.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald strongly advocated for the Centre to form part of a conservative government in the Reich under Hans Luther, using his role as head of the DGB to claim widespread union support.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] For this he received a cold reception at the October 1924 congress of the DGB's industrial unions and was attacked by Heinrich Imbusch, head of the miners' union.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Ultimately the unions passed a resolution declaring neutrality in political affairs and Stegerwald was forced to walk back his previous statements.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] When the first Luther cabinet was invested the following January, the majority of the labour representatives among the Centre's Reichstag delegation did not support it.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] At the Centre Party congress in November 1925 Stegerwald was heckled by Joseph Wirth, outspoken leader of the Centre left, who accused him of giving a pass to nationalist extremism.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] After the collapse of the Luther cabinet the following year, Stegerwald's perspective on cooperation with the conservative right changed.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He no longer considered the German National People's Party "worthy of carrying Christian spirit in public life", finding the party both anti-Catholic and uninterested in serious advocacy for the Protestant churches or Christian values.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In December 1928, the Centre Party congress was tasked with electing a new party chairman.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] The executive unanimously recommended Stegerwald.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] This choice was intended to be a fig leaf to the unions and facilitate Stegerwald's movement out of the DGB leadership into full-time politics, which he had long sought.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] However, the party national committee rejected Stegerwald: this was at least in part due to the predominance of civil servants on the committee, whose interests Stegerwald had unexpectedly opposed the previous year.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He was also opposed for reasons of personality as well as his opposition to church interference in the party.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] The party hierarchy considered several alternatives and ultimately put forward three names to a floor vote: Stegerwald, his rival in the unions Joseph Joos, and prelate Ludwig Kaas.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald received 42 votes, Joos 92, and Kaas 182.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Despite this defeat, in January 1929, Stegerwald was elected head of the Centre Reichstag faction.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He resigned his position as head of the DGB and in the unions, finally completing his move to full-time politics.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In April he became Minister for Transport in the new Great Coalition under Hermann Müller.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] When the government fell in March 1930, Stegerwald was promoted to Labour Minister by new Chancellor Heinrich Brüning, who had been Stegerwald's assistant and protege earlier in the 1920s.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In this role he was both tasked with implementing the government's harsh austerity response to the Great Depression in Germany, which entailed reductions in wages and rolling back labour rights, while also seeking to maintain the welfare state for the millions of unemployed despite harsh cutbacks.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] It was also in this time that he achieved the long-sought for cooperation with the moderate and religious elements of the Protestant right following the secession from the DNVP of the Conservative People's Party and CSVD, who collaborated in the Brüning government.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald remained Labour Minister until the cabinet's dismissal in May 1932.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Following Hitler's appointment as Chancellor in January 1933, Stegerwald was attacked by SA storm troopers at an election rally in Krefeld on 21 February.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] The following month, he helped lead negotiations with the Nazi Party to secure the Centre's support for the Enabling Act of 1933 which handed *de facto* dictatorial power to Hitler.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] From 1933 to 1934 he was indicted, along with Wilhelm Marx and Heinrich Brauns, in the trial of the Cologne *Volksverein Verlag* in his capacity as board member of the National Association for Catholic Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He was on the list of politicians to be purged during the Night of the Long Knives, but received warning and disappeared into exile for three months.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He retired to Franconia during the regime, and in letters to former colleagues urged church leaders to appease the government for fear of the churches' dissolution.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Following the 20 July plot, he was temporarily arrested under the *Aktion Gitter*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] From August to October 1944 he was detained by the Gestapo in Würzburg prison before being released.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Following the end of the Second World War, the American occupation authority appointed the 71-year-old Stegerwald administrator of the Lower Franconia district.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He became leader of the "Würzburg group" which proved instrumental in the foundation of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria in the late summer and autumn of 1945.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] In Stegerwald's speeches and writing it was clear he considered the new party the fulfillment of his "People's Party" concept of 1920, serving as a "bridge" between denominations, classes, and generations; he coined the name "Christian Social Union".
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Despite the desire of some Catholic labour leaders to found a united labour party with the socialist unions, and of other Catholic leaders to re-found the Centre Party, Stegerwald's model was ultimately taken up nationwide in the form of the Christian Democratic Union of Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Adam Stegerwald died of pneumonia in December 1945.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] He has been honoured extensively, with streets named after him in numerous towns and cities across Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Two political education foundations, the Adam Stegerwald Circle and Stegerwald Foundation, are named in his honour.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] A neighbourhood in Cologne, *Stegerwaldsiedlung*, is also named for him.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Two buildings in Würzburg are named *Adam-Stegerwald-Haus*: the office of the regional CSU branch as well as a student accommodation building.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] Another building in Königswinter, originally acquired by Jakob Kaiser and used by Catholic welfare and political associations in the Weimar period, was renamed *Adam-Stegerwald-Haus* in 1948 after its acquisition by the new German Trade Union Confederation.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adam-stegerwald] After housing a number of different organisations over the decades, the building was sold in 2015 and converted into a nursing home, retaining its name.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] His parents divorced when he was three years old.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] Having finished his studies in Berlin and Göttingen in 1825, he joined the Prussian Guards Uhlans regiment as a One-year volunteer and afterwards entered civil service at the Kammergericht.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] In 1830, he was appointed *Landrat* official in the Uckermark district.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] In 1833, he became Vice-president of the Pomeranian Stralsund government region.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] One year later, he assumed the position of President in the Aix-la-Chapelle (Aachen) region, from 1838 in Merseburg, Saxony.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] In 1840 he became governor (*Oberpräsident*) of the Grand Duchy of Posen.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] In 1842 Arnim was called back to Berlin to be appointed Prussian State Minister of the Interior.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] Nevertheless, he resigned in 1845 because his plans for a constitution for Prussia were at odds with King Frederick William IV's romantic ideals.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] When the March Revolution broke out in 1848, his services were again in demand.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] From 19 March 1848, he acted as the first Prussian Minister-President and Foreign Minister.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] However, he again resigned within a few days after the king chose to place himself at the head of the national movement.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] A member of the Provincial Brandenburg *Landtag* assembly since 1839, Arnim from 18 May to 10 June 1848 was a representative for Prenzlau in the Frankfurt Parliament and also was a member of the short-lived Erfurt Union Parliament in 1850.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] He belonged to the newly established Prussian House of Representatives from 1849 and later joined the House of Lords chamber of the Prussian Parliament.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] Arnim is known to this day for his remarks as Prussian Interior Minister during the *Vormärz* era concerning Heinrich Heine's poem *The Silesian Weavers*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] The verses were published in the *Vorwärts!* weekly newspaper after an 1844 riot in the Province of Silesia, which later also inspired the drama *The Weavers* by Gerhart Hauptmann.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] Subsequently, the Royal Prussian Kammergericht banned the poem, which in 1846 led to a prison sentence for a person who had dared to publicly recite it.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] He married Countess Anna Caroline von der Schulenburg (1804–1886), a daughter of Count Hans Günther Werner von der Schulenburg.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] One of his children was politician Adolf von Arnim-Boitzenburg, who was in 1880 for a short time president of German Reichstag.
[src:adam-stegerwald/adolf-heinrich-von-arnim-boitzenburg] Arnim died on 8 January 1868 at his Boitzenburg estate.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The mass arrests of *Aktion Gitter* were neither unprecedented nor a spontaneous government response to the assassination attempt of July 1944, but the working through of long-standing policies.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Leading politicians from the Weimar years had been identified on a so-called government "A-list" as early as 1935/36, divided into sub-categories A-1, A-2 and A-3.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] At the outbreak of the Second World War in 1939 the Gestapo had arrested between 2,000 and 4,000 people whose names appeared on List A-1.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] These were identified as "enemies of the state" and placed in "protective custody", in most cases in the Buchenwald concentration camp.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] However, most of these had been released by the summer of 1940.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Nevertheless, Hitler gave notice in April 1942 that "if a mutiny were to break out today somewhere in the country", it would meet with an immediate response (*Sofortmaßnahmen*).
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Directly following the outbreak of civil arrest or similar disturbances, all leading men from the [left-wing] opposition, and indeed also those from the Catholic political tradition would be arrested, removed from their homes and sent for execution.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Additionally all concentration camp inmates would be shot along with all criminals, whether they were in state detention or at liberty at the time.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] On 14 August 1944 SS Chief Himmler received the mandate to have former Social Democratic (SPD) and Communist Party (KPD) officials detained.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The mass arrest, estimated to cover more than 5,000 former politicians, was to take no account of whether or not those detained were still engaged in opposition activity, and was not connected with the search underway for the July assassination plotters.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Three days later all leading Gestapo officers in the country received a secret telex from Department 4 of the Reich Security Main Office (*Reichssicherheitshauptamt*; RSHA).
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Those aged more than 70, those who were ill and those who had been "of service to the system" [since 1933] should be spared from arrest, however.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The arrests were to happen nationwide during the early hours of 22 August.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Orders were that detainees should then be taken without delay to the nearest concentration camp and taken into what was designated "protective custody" by the RHSA.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Additionally, by 25 August Gestapo officers of the RHSA should then report the total numbers arrested, analysed according to political party and according to political functions.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Himmler's orders arrived under the heading *Aktion Gitter*.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] On 21 August the order was extended so that pre-1933 assembly members from the old Centre Party were also to be detained, although this broadening of the scope of the action was partially rescinded two days later.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The arrests went ahead as instructed, in the small hours, either by Gestapo officers acting alone or by Gestapo officers acting in partnership with local police officers.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Estimates indicate that approximately 5,000 were arrested across Germany, and most were promptly delivered to the closest concentration camp.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Some of the concentration camps receiving the largest numbers of *Gitter* detainees were at Neuengamme near Hamburg (650), Buchenwald near Weimar (742) and Dachau near Munich (860).
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] In Berlin detainees were taken to the main Gestapo prison in Prince Albrecht Street, and a large number from this area were also sent to Ravensbrück.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The arrests had in many cases been undertaken on the basis of out-of-date lists: many of those arrested were old and ill, and had not been involved in politics for more than ten years.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Some of those arrested had already been arrested during the immediate aftermath of the Nazi takeover in 1933, but subsequently released.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Others found themselves arrested for the first time.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Many were released after a few months in response to protests from family members.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The way in which the mass arrests were carried out triggered such popular resentment that one week later on 30 August 1944, Ernst Kaltenbrunner ordered a review that led to some mitigation.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Overall the approach of the ruling Nazi Party remained inconsistent and unpredictable, however.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] On the one hand, many of the detainees were soon released in response to massive protests from their families and friends.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] But on the other, because of the inhuman conditions in the concentration camps during the winter of 1944/45, many of those who remained in detention died.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] That is what happened to Johanna Tesch and Joseph Roth.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Former national Reichstag Gitter detainees who did not survive the concentration camps included Otto Gerig, Karl Mache and Heinrich Jasper.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The Hamburg education reformer Kurt Adams was a Gitter victim who possibly did not even live to experience that year's winter.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] As the end of the war approached the authorities evacuated concentration camps in areas about to be overrun by enemy armies.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Evacuation was accomplished through a succession of forced marches, which came to be known as death marches.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Camp inmates unable to complete these death marches were simply shot.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Former member of the Reichstag Friedrich Puchta initially survived his death march out of Dachau and lived to see liberation, after which he was immediately hospitalised.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] He perished shortly thereafter as a direct consequence of his internment at Dachau.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Other *Gitter* detainees perished when the SS *Cap Arcona*, by then used as a prison ship and moored off Lübeck, was sunk by the British Royal Air Force the day before the German military surrender.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] *Aktion Gitter* was therefore a government reprisal that ended in death for many of those caught up in it.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Politician victims of *Aktion Gitter* who survived the experience and re-emerged as national politicians in the German Federal Republic (West Germany), following its establishment in 1949, include Konrad Adenauer (CDU), Paul Löbe (SPD) and Kurt Schumacher (SPD).
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] The historian Stefanie Schüler-Springorum, writing in 2005, noted that *Aktion Gitter* had at that time only been researched "selectively" for northern Germany.
[src:adam-stegerwald/aktion-gitter] Subsequently other historians have endorsed the view that *Gitter* has not yet been conclusively researched.
